Guidance and specifications on how to embed documentation content within the UML model.
Guidance and specifications on how to embed documentation content within the UML model.

Adding documentation to your model is easy. Every "element" in your model (e.g. all classes, attributes, associations) should have some textual documentation in the "notes" field of the model. (See documentation at https://www.seegrid.csiro.au/twiki/bin/view/AppSchemas/ModelDocumentation for more information and screen shots of where the notes should be created for the different model element types).
The tool used to auto-generate documentation from the model expects to find notes in only these places. You need not have comments for every model element but it is good practice to do so and it gives the auto-generated documentation a much more usable and complete appearance.

The GASDoc tool (see https://www.seegrid.csiro.au/twiki/bin/view/AppSchemas/ModelDocumentation) is a tool for generating API documentation for GML Application Schema (GAS) models.
It is similar to API documentation tools that exist for modern programming languages (like Javadoc for Java). It takes an input in the form of an XML document and generates a set of linked HTML pages as output. The input is an XMI (XML Metadata Interchange) representation of a GML Application Schema UML model.

See
https://www.seegrid.csiro.au/twiki/bin/view/AppSchemas/ModelDocumentation
for more information on the model documentation and generation process.

Open the EA project file for the project you wish to get the new package into. This can be an existing project or a new project.

Periodically you will need to synchronise your working replica with the main project file. This will primarily occur for one of two reasons: * The main project file has changed (eg. modified by someone else) * You have modifications you want to commit.
In these cases, you need to synchronise by (i) (outside EA) use your SVN client (TortoiseSVN) to do an SVN "update" on the design-master (.EAP file), so as to get any changes made by anyone else that have been checked in (ii) select "Tools-->Manage .EAP File-->Synchronize replicas" from the menu bar, and then specifying the design-master (main project file) in the dialogue. This will cause changes between the two files to be merged.
Note: Synchronising is a two-way process. Any changes in your replica will be propogated to the main project file and vice-versa. If you do not want your working changes to be added to the project, make sure you do not commit the main project .EAP file after synchronising.

Creating a local copy to hack can be done two ways:
1) turn off version control on package, export to new location, reload from this location
or
2) Follow the "Create a new release" procedure, but place the new version under "branches" instead of "tags"
The second approach allows you to share hacked versions without making changes to the source release or consensus position on the trunk.
